{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ef3bde79-9b0a-4381-8848-6d3e3ec6ea0f","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI `ContentPage` property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need **platform-specific** configuration:\n\n### iOS\nUse the iOS platform-specific `UseSafeArea` property:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n    Padding=\"0\">\n```\n\n### Android\nAndroid requires opting into edge-to-edge drawing. In your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    \n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Also check for:\n- **`Padding` on the page or layout** — set it explicitly to `0`\n- **Shell chrome** — if using `Shell`, hide the nav bar:\n  ```xml\n  Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n  ```\n- **`Aspect` on the Image** — use `AspectFill` to fill the entire area:\n  ```xml\n  <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n  ```\n\nThe iOS piece alone may fix your issue if you're only testing on iPhone. Both platforms need their own opt-in for content behind system bars.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"24ea0e81-0e8e-409e-8d74-33c133c49cd0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is not a standard MAUI property — they might be confusing it with something else, or it might be a newer API. Actually, in .NET MAUI there isn't a built-in `SafeAreaEdges` property on ContentPage by default. \n\n\n2. The actual approach depends on the platform — iOS and Android handle this differently. On iOS, I need to use platform-specific markup to disable safe area handling, while on Android I need to configure the window to extend behind system bars and handle the insets manually. I'm considering whether there might be a `Padding` property being applied somewhere, or if the Shell navigation is adding extra chrome that's pushing content down—those are the most common culprits when content doesn't reach the edges as expected.","outputTokens":1168,"requestId":"A432:1D28CE:521D81:5F9A92:69F0083E"},"id":"7ef84c6e-8abd-4b08-aba0-e1546c6784af","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:07:33.008Z","parentId":"a5437249-94ed-45f0-a965-5a7b5c302bed"}
